Fix AOT trimming warnings in these files in `/tmp/sv-c597498712f2407bae06c6ba7e853dba/before/`. Replace `JsonSerializer` calls with AOT-safe alternatives.

## File 1: ArmEnvironment.cs

Line 80: `public override string ToString() => JsonSerializer.Serialize(this);`

Replace with a manual JSON construction using Utf8JsonWriter to avoid JsonSerializer:

```csharp
public override string ToString()
{
    var buffer = new System.Buffers.ArrayBufferWriter<byte>();
    using (var writer = new Utf8JsonWriter(buffer))
    {
        writer.WriteStartObject();
        writer.WriteString("Endpoint"u8, Endpoint.ToString());
        writer.WriteString("Audience"u8, Audience);
        writer.WriteString("DefaultScope"u8, DefaultScope);
        writer.WriteEndObject();
    }
    return System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(buffer.WrittenSpan);
}
```

You'll also need to add `using System.Buffers;` if it's not already present. Since the file uses `System.Text.Json`, the Utf8JsonWriter should be available.

Actually, the current return statement is an expression-bodied method. Replace the entire line. Make sure the `using System.Text.Json;` is already there (it is).

## File 2: ArmClientOptions.cs

Line 52: `var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);`

Replace the JsonSerializer.Deserialize call with JsonDocument.Parse and manual traversal. The code block starting around line 48 is:

```csharp
var assembly = Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly();
using (Stream stream = assembly.GetManifestResourceStream(profile.GetManifestName()))
{
    var span = BinaryData.FromStream(stream).ToMemory().Span;
    var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);
    var armProfile = allProfile["resource-manager"];
    foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile)
    {
        var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Key;
        var element = keyValuePair.Value;
```

Replace with:
```csharp
var assembly = Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly();
using (Stream stream = assembly.GetManifestResourceStream(profile.GetManifestName()))
{
    var span = BinaryData.FromStream(stream).ToMemory();
    using var document = JsonDocument.Parse(span);
    var armProfile = document.RootElement.GetProperty("resource-manager");
    foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile.EnumerateObject())
    {
        var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Name;
        var element = keyValuePair.Value;
```

Note: Changed `span` from `.Span` (ReadOnlySpan<byte>) to just the Memory<byte> result (since JsonDocument.Parse accepts ReadOnlyMemory<byte>). Also changed `keyValuePair.Key` to `keyValuePair.Name` since JsonProperty uses `Name` not `Key`.

## File 3: Extensions/ArmClientBuilderExtensions.cs

Line 30: `return builder.RegisterClientFactory<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions>(configuration);`

This calls `IAzureClientFactoryBuilderWithConfiguration<TConfiguration>.RegisterClientFactory` which is from Azure.Core and is marked with `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]`. Since this is calling an external API that's fundamentally not AOT-compatible, we need to mark this method with those attributes too.

Add `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]` attributes to the method:

Change:
```csharp
public static IAzureClientBuilder<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions> AddArmClient<TBuilder, TConfiguration>(this TBuilder builder, TConfiguration configuration)
    where TBuilder : IAzureClientFactoryBuilderWithConfiguration<TConfiguration>
{
    return builder.RegisterClientFactory<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions>(configuration);
}
```

To:
```csharp
[RequiresUnreferencedCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values is not supported with trimming. Use the Configuration Binder source generator instead.")]
[RequiresDynamicCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values requires generating dynamic code at runtime, for example instantiating generic types.")]
public static IAzureClientBuilder<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions> AddArmClient<TBuilder, TConfiguration>(this TBuilder builder, TConfiguration configuration)
    where TBuilder : IAzureClientFactoryBuilderWithConfiguration<TConfiguration>
{
    return builder.RegisterClientFactory<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions>(configuration);
}
```

The file already has `using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;`.

## File 4: LongRunningOperation files (4 files)

These 4 files all have the same pattern at line 61:
```csharp
var lroDetails = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default).ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>();
return lroDetails["id"];
```

`BinaryData.ToObjectFromJson<T>()` uses JsonSerializer internally and has IL2026/IL3050 warnings.

Replace with JsonDocument.Parse:
```csharp
using var lroDocument = JsonDocument.Parse(ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default));
return lroDocument.RootElement.GetProperty("id").GetString();
```

The 4 files are:
1. `ManagementGroup/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ManagementGroupsArmOperation.cs`
2. `ManagementGroup/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ManagementGroupsArmOperationOfT.cs`
3. `Resources/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ResourcesArmOperation.cs`
4. `Resources/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ResourcesArmOperationOfT.cs`

In each file, the `GetOperationId` method contains:
```csharp
var lroDetails = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default).ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>();
return lroDetails["id"];
```

Replace those two lines with:
```csharp
using var lroDocument = JsonDocument.Parse(ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default));
return lroDocument.RootElement.GetProperty("id").GetString();
```

You may need to add `using System.Text.Json;` if it's not already present in those files.

IMPORTANT:
- Do NOT use `#pragma warning disable` or `[UnconditionalSuppressMessage]` for any IL warnings.
- Only edit the files specified, using the `edit` tool.
- Make precise, surgical changes.

